{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5e67015-16ca-49e7-9793-5a114407064b","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options available via `--auth`:\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API, no auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n\n# With Azure AD single-org auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n\n# With Azure AD B2C\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth IndividualB2C\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options including `--use-controllers`, `--no-https`, and OpenAPI settings.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5e345ead-b3cd-455d-8ae3-c93d66b1c8a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":312,"requestId":"4807:81B49:EC8B7:11ABD6:69EABD74"},"id":"1870f2a1-6769-45f4-96b0-4fecf208fafc","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:46:53.035Z","parentId":"d5eb7466-6553-4fe0-9d0f-40ff503015ac"}
